            <h4>Main Research Questions</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Are there issues stopping users from signing up?</li>
                <li>Can users find where to sign up? Are we promoting sign up right?</li>
                <li>Are there market specificities we should be aware of?</li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Methodologies used</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Click tests on <a href="https://www.userzoom.com/">Userzoom</a>.</li>
                <li>Usability testing.</li>
                <li>Previous in-house research into local experiences.
                </li>
                <li>Quantitative data from <a
                        href="https://analytics.google.com/analytics/">Google Analytics</a> and
                    <a
                            href="https://www.clicktale.com/">Clicktale.</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Key takeaways</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>No need to go too heavy on the Sign ups CTAs. Users can find it already, and it's getting a bit too
                    much.
                </li>
                <li>We are not always promoting sign up in the right context, and users
                    sometimes find the copy uninspiring.
                </li>
                <li>Drop out rates on mobile (which accounts for 70% of H&M's visitors) is 30% higher than on desktop:
                    no wonder, when it takes 40s longer to sign up, and there's severe usability issues (especially on
                    Android).
                </li>
                <li>In some countries, we must provide more sign-up options.
                </li>
            </ul>


            <h4>Prioritise</h4>
            <p>Based on those insights, the team and I established our priority. Then,
                I did a quick showcase of the research at our Sprint Demo to help our stakeholders
                understand the decisions.</p>


