            <h4>Opportunity</h4>
            <p>In the winter of 2020, the membership will be launched in a country where email usage is very low, and
                tying the loyalty program and sign up to the dominant social media platform is key
                (I won't reveal details or show designs as the launch is still confidential).</p>
            <h4>Competitive analysis</h4>
            <p>I did some reading to understand the market better, and got help from H&M staff in that market to examine how competitors are using
            the social media platform for their loyalty program.</p>
            <h4>User flows</h4>
            <p>I worked closely with our IT Architect and Developers to draw up user flows. There were a lot of scenarios to account for, and it was a real challenge to keep the experience frictionless within the limits of the social media platform we were working with, and of our own systems.
                       </p>
            <h4>Sketch, Design Review, Prototype</h4>
            <p>I sketched out the main flows to and from the social media platform, as well as different possibilities for a new layout for the sign up form. I
                selected three
                thanks to feedback received in Design Review, then prepared prototypes to test.</p>
            <h4>Usability Testing</h4>
            <p>One layout resulted in less errors than the others. However, no clear
                insights emerged around some of the tricky points in the journey, like signing up directly from the
                social
                media platform, or merging accounts if the email address is already in our systems. But it was expected:
                to gain time and reduce costs, I had to compromise
                in recruitment, and participants were from the market, but based in the US.

            </p>

